This project presents an end-to-end analysis of global oil and petroleum price trends from 2020 to 2026. It combines historical data analysis with real-time data integration to provide a comprehensive view of how the energy market behaves under economic and geopolitical pressure.

The analysis explores how major global disruptions, including economic shocks, geopolitical tensions, and conflicts affecting key energy regions, have influenced price movements over time. The results show that oil prices do not follow a stable trend, but instead move in cycles shaped by external events and changing supply-demand dynamics.

In addition to historical analysis, the project includes an interactive Power BI dashboard that allows users to explore trends, identify turning points, and understand volatility across different periods.

To extend the project beyond static analysis, a Streamlit web application was developed to present the insights in an interactive format. The app integrates a live API to track current oil prices in real time, ensuring that the analysis remains connected to ongoing market conditions.

An automation component was also implemented to send WhatsApp notifications with the latest oil price updates, demonstrating how data can be used not only for analysis but also for real-time monitoring and alerting.

Key Insights
Oil prices are highly sensitive to geopolitical tensions and global conflicts
The market follows cyclical patterns rather than a consistent upward or downward trend
Volatility is a defining characteristic of the energy sector
External factors such as economic disruptions and supply chain issues play a major role in price movements
Tools and Technologies
Python for data analysis and automation
Power BI for data visualization and dashboard development
Streamlit for building the web application
APIs for real-time data integration
Conclusion

This project highlights the importance of combining historical analysis with real-time data and external context. Understanding oil price behavior requires more than analyzing past trends; it requires continuous monitoring of global events and their impact on the market.
